you can use this line instead your echo line in php 

     echo &#39;&lt;a href=&quot;#&quot; onclick=&quot;show(&#39;.&quot;&#39;&quot;.$f.&quot;&#39;&quot;.&#39;)&quot;&gt;&#39;.$f.&#39;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&#39;;
it will solve the issue

Your code will print something like that:

    &lt;a hre=&quot;#&quot; onclick=&quot;show(filename)&quot;&gt;filename&lt;/a&gt;

&lt;br&gt;Where **filename** in the onclick considered as a variable name because you don&#39;t wrap it in the string quotes.&lt;br&gt;
So the solution is to add quotes around the php variable:

    echo &#39;&lt;a href=&quot;#&quot; onClick=&quot;show(\&#39;&#39; . $f . &#39;\&#39;)&quot;&gt;&#39;.$f.&#39;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&#39;;

and in a more readable way:

    printf(&#39;&lt;a href= &quot;#&quot; onClick=&quot;show(\&#39;%s\&#39;);&quot;&gt;%s&lt;/a&gt; &#39;, $f, $f);

Last thing remember that you may need to use **[htmlspecialchars][1]** before printing data to HTML.


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.htmlspecialchars.php

